stix:STIX_Header.stix:Title: Analysis of three loader files, three embedded PE files, and three C2 URLs
stix:STIX_Header.stix:Description:
On 29 August 2013, a Corporate eFax themed phishing email was observed. The email contained a malicious attachment file that was found to contain a loader for an embedded PE files that is decoded, decompressed, and executed at run-time.
The following day, this loader, along with two other similar loader files, were also submitted for analysis. It was found that their embedded PE files are downloaders that call back to the following URLs via port 443 using https: thisisyourwife.co.uk rpduk.com whitewaterexcitement.com
This document incorporates data originally released as MIFR-310435.

Filename: Embedded_1.exe
Antivirus Identifier: Kaspersky: HEUR:Trojan‐Downloader.Win32.Generic Microsoft: TrojanDownloader:Win32/Upatre.A
This file is never written to disk and therefore has no file name. It is referred to as "Embedded_1.exe" in this report.
This file is loaded into memory by the file "Fax_08292013_821.exe" and executed. "Embedded_1.exe" copies the loader file to the user's %TEMP% directory and gives it the file name "hcbnaf.exe". The new file is executed and the original file "Fax_08292013_821.exe" is deleted.
"Embedded_1.exe" calls back to the URL "thisisyourwife.co.uk" via port 443 (https) and downloads a file. The downloaded file is saved to the current directory of the loader file "hcbnaf.exe" with the file name "hgnddkje.exe" and executed.
